            <div class="ins_notes">
                <span class="note" id="note-1"><a href="#ref-1">[1]</a> The decrees honour a hipparch, the overall commander of the Athenian cavalry, here a single official, but usually two; see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII31/949"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 1, 949</a>, the only other Assembly decree of the hellenistic period honouring hipparchs (but for decrees of the cavalry themselves see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/1264"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 1264</a> honouring treasurers of Athena, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/21525"><i>SEG</i> 21.525</a> and (?) <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/AgoraXVI/270"><i>Agora</i> 16.270</a> honouring their commanders; note also the decree of the squadron of Tarantinoi honouring the cavalry commanders, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/46167"><i>SEG</i> 46.167</a>). His name is unfortunately not preserved, but both decrees mention that he was in office in the archonship of Symmachos (188/7), decree 2 (of the cavalry) is dated to the first month of the following year (l. 13), and decree 1 (of the Assembly) should date to about the same time. The inscription, however, is a work of Tracy's "Cutter of Agora I 6006", datable to 169/8-135/4, implying that it must represent the reinscription (in circumstances that can not be recovered) of decrees passed a generation earlier. Our translation mostly follows the text of <i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup>, but diverges in ll. 16 and 42-43 (nn. 4 and 7 below).</span>
<span class="note" id="note-2"><a href="#ref-2">[2]</a> The <a class="highlight" href="http://agora.ascsa.net/id/agora/monument/northwest%20corner%20and%20the%20hermes">Herms</a> were located to the north-west of the Agora (<i>Agora</i> III, pp. 103-8); cf. <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII3/949"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 949</a>, placed in the same location, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/21525"><i>SEG</i> 21.525</a>, placed in the Poseidonion and the stoa of the Herms; cf. <a class="highlight" href="/browse/bysource/ParkerPoly/">Parker, <i>Polytheism</i></a>, 392 n. 23.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-3"><a href="#ref-3">[3]</a> Member of a prominent family of hellenistic Athens, see C. Habicht, <i>Studien</i> (1982), 194-97.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-4"><a href="#ref-4">[4]</a> The decree of around the same period honouring the hipparchs, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/AgoraXVI/2701"><i>Agora</i> XVI 270</a> begins (l. 4) with a reference to their sacrifice of εἰσιτητήρια, "entry sacrifices", a type of sacrifice commonly made at the beginning of a term of office, and they should also be restored here rather than [σω]τήρια ("salutary", of sacrifices by managers of the Mysteries, e.g.  <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII31/1182"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 1, 1182</a>, and priests of Asklepios, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII2/950"><i>IG</i> II<sup>2</sup> 950</a>). This was tentatively recognised by C. Habicht, <i>AM</i> 76 (1961), 143. [Lambert].</span>
<span class="note" id="note-5"><a href="#ref-5">[5]</a> An athletic festival in honour of Nemesis of Rhamnous. Cf. <a class="highlight" href="/browse/bysource/ParkerPoly/">Parker, <i>Polytheism</i></a>, 476. It is unclear whether the cavalry participated at the festival, or were on guard duty at it.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-6"><a href="#ref-6">[6]</a> The Hermaia were probably mentioned as location of a proclamation of the honours. Sacrifices to Hermes, "Hermaia", were were commonly made by users of gymnasia (cf. <a class="highlight" href="/browse/bysource/ParkerPoly/">Parker, <i>Polytheism</i></a>, 251), and there is provision for one in the Lykeion in the city's sacrificial calendar, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/5248a"><i>SEG</i> 52.48A F6 l.4</a>. It is attractive to connect these Hermaia with the Herms by which decree 1 was to be erected (l. 11); and they may also have been the Hermaia at which Demetrios of Phaleron the Younger, who had among other offices been hipparch, won a chariot victory, <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII34/281"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 4, 281</a> l. 44. For a local 5th-century sacrificial calendar providing for end-of-year "Hermaia" cf. <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGI3/246"><i>IG</i> I<sup>3</sup> 246</a>, 29-33. For end-year offerings to Hermes by ephebes in the Hellenistic period see <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII34/357"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 4, 357</a>; see also <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/IGII34/368"><i>IG</i> II<sup>3</sup> 4, 368</a>.</span>
<span class="note" id="note-7"><a href="#ref-7">[7]</a> What "court" this was is obscure. <i>IG</i> restores one copy of this decree to be inscribed by the Herms (as l. 11) and another "in the court ...", but now that it is clear that this is a reinscription, the copy by the Herms is no longer compelling. The reinscription may have brought together two decrees originally inscribed in different locations. Rather than two locations specified for the original copy of decree 2, the end of l. 42 is more likely to have included a reference to the secretaries of the cavalry commanders, who were commissioned to inscribe <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/21525"><i>SEG</i> 21.525</a> and <a class="highlight" href="/inscription/SEG/46167"><i>SEG</i> 46.167</a>:
ἀναγράψαι τόδε [τὸ ψήφισμα ἐν στήλει λιθίνηι τοὺς γραμματεῖς τῶν ἱππάρχων, καὶ στῆσαι] | ἐν τῆι αὐλῆι τῶν -. [Lambert].</span>
            </div>
            

